\begin_layout Standard
A different formulation considers the site selection problem as a 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-median problem, in which base station location is the only decision variable
 considered.
 To each of the candidates solutions, an installation cost is also associated.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-median problem constitutes seeking 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 different locations each time, regardless of how distant the sites are.
 The problem is to select one candidate site from each region to install
 a base station such that the traffic capacity and the size of the covered
 area are maximized with the lowest installation cost.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Proposed solutions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Aydin et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Aydin:Heuristic.Optimization.Of.WCDMA"

\end_inset

 propose a solution to the 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-median problem based on three meta-heuristic algorithms; a genetic algorithm,
 simulated annealing, and tabu search.
 Their experimental study focuses on performance comparison between the
 three algorithms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A solution to the set covering problem is proposed by Hao et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "minimum.set.covering.problem:1997"

\end_inset

.
 A simulated annealing implementation was developed to solve the formulated
 combinatorial problem.
 The results presented demonstrate the feasibility of the proposed approach.
 Tutschku 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "minimum.set.covering.problem:1998"

\end_inset

 presents a specialized greedy algorithm to solve the same problem.
 This work is part of the implementation of a planning tool prototype.
 Mathar and Niessen 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "minimum.set.covering.problem:2000"

\end_inset

 propose a solution based on integer linear programming, which they claim
 finds optimal solutions in most cases.
 They also introduce simulated annealing as an approximate optimization
 technique.
 This approach substitutes linear programming whenever an exact solution
 is out of reach because of the complexity of the problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Amaldi et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "amaldi:planning.umts.base.station.location"

\end_inset

 offer a discussion about the computational results of two different heuristics:
 greedy search and tabu search.
 The problem formulation is based on a set of candidate sites where the
 base stations can be installed, an estimation of the traffic distribution
 and a propagation description of the area to be covered.
 Some years later, the same authors 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Amaldi:Radio.planning.and.coveraga.optimization"

\end_inset

 extended the problem formulation by also considering base station configuration
 and hardware characteristics.
 In both works, they propose a mixed integer programming model with which
 they aim to maximize the trade-off between total traffic covered and total
 installation costs.
 The only difference between the models is the constraint definition of
 the linear program, where the constraints in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "amaldi:planning.umts.base.station.location"

\end_inset

 are a subset of the constraints in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Amaldi:Radio.planning.and.coveraga.optimization"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, Whitaker et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "GA.for.antenna.placement:2005"

\end_inset

 focus on providing the required service coverage at the lowest possible
 financial cost.
 Their framework supports the use of any multiple objective optimization
 algorithm which seeks to approximate a Pareto front.
 The performance of four different algorithms is explored, namely SEAMO,
 SPEA2, NSGA-II and PESA.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Optimizing antenna parameters
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are many antenna parameters that control the coverage and interference
 in the network, since the antenna shapes the emitted energy.
 Two important parameters are the azimuth angle and the elevation angle
 (or tilt) of the antenna.
 The antenna azimuth (shown in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Antenna-azimuth"

\end_inset

) is the direction in which the main beam of the horizontal pattern points
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "WCDMAforUMTS_RadioAccessForThirdGenerationMobileCommunications"

\end_inset

.
 The antenna tilt (shown in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Antenna-tilt"

\end_inset

) is defined as the angle of the main beam of the antenna relative to the
 horizontal plane 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "WCDMAforUMTS_RadioAccessForThirdGenerationMobileCommunications"

\end_inset

.
 Both of these parameters have a great influence on network quality, although
 antenna tilt requires less effort to implement, since most modern radio
 networks already support remote electrical tilt.
 The adjustment of these two parameters optimize some important aspects
 of the network, namely:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
path loss between the base station and the mobile phone, since less power
 is required for a connection, hence more power is available for traffic;
 and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
interference between neighboring cells, which leads to an overall capacity
 increase.
\end_layout

